SIMPLE: mimical
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mimical
<hw>Mim"ic*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
}</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mimicus</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/
mime: cf. F. <ets>mimique</ets>. See <er>Mime</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Imitative; mimetic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Oft, in her absence, <qex>mimic</qex> fancy wakes⟦br⟧
To imitate her.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Man is, of all creatures, the most <qex>mimical</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Consisting of, or formed by, imitation; imitated;
<as>as, <ex>mimic</ex> gestures</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Mimic</xex>
hootings.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Wordsworth.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>Imitative; characterized by
resemblance to other forms; -- applied to crystals which by twinning
resemble simple forms of a higher grade of symmetry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Mimic</xex> often implies something droll or
ludicrous, and is less dignified than <xex>imitative</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mimic beetle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a beetle
that feigns death when disturbed, esp. the species of <gen>Hister</gen>
and allied genera.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mimic</ent>⟦br⟧
